The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Business | After-tax profit up 12%
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       After-tax profit up 12%
          OUR CORRESPONDENT                              
	Mumbai, April 18: The infotech industry looks set to ride out the bumps on the road created by all the spooky talk about a recession in the US.        
	After Infosys announced better than expected results last week, Wipro said today its profit after tax during the year ended March 31 had risen 12 per cent to Rs 3,283 crore.        
	Revenues for the year grew to Rs 19,957 crore  in line with market expectations.        
	During the fourth quarter, after-tax profit rose 3 per cent year-on-year to Rs 880 crore. Revenues in the quarter rose 32 per cent to Rs 5,700 crore.        
	Revenues of Wipros global IT business in rupee terms stood at Rs 3,833 crore, a 26 per cent hike year-on-year. During the quarter, Wipros IT business won three multi-year multi-million dollar deals, the company said.         
	Global IT services and products added 29 clients in the quarter. India, West Asia and Asia Pacific businesses recorded 41 per cent year-on-year growth in revenues at Rs 1,096 crore.        
	Revenue of Wipros Global IT business in dollar terms amounted to $3.39 billion, a 38 per cent growth year-on-year. In rupee terms, revenues stood at Rs 13,642 crore.        
	Wipro chairman Azim Premji said he remained cautious but resilient in the near term. The global economic outlook has changed significantly since the beginning of this calendar year, Premji said. It poses new challenges and opens up newer opportunities.        
	Revenues for the combined IT business achieved $4.3 billion. For the quarter, we recorded revenues of $959.9 million, which was ahead of our guidance of $955 million. During 2007-08, we saw robust growth in all our key verticals and differentiated service lines, Premji added.                                                                                                                                                   
